    <exercises xml:id="practice-isomorph" permid="tse">
      <title>Practice Problems</title>

      <exercise permid="ejg">
        <statement>
          <p permid="FUR">
            Prove that <m>\Z \equiv 2\Z</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="kIm">
          <p permid="qbZ">
            We define the function <m>f:\Z \to 2\Z</m> by <m>f(x) = 2x</m>.  This is clearly a bijection.  Further, it satisfies the <em>homomorphism property</em>:            <m>f(x+y) = 2(x+y) = 2x + 2y = f(x) + f(y)</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="Kqp">
        <statement>
          <p permid="mca">
            I'm thinking of a group <m>G = \{a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h\}</m> with an operation I'm calling <m>\oplus</m>.  It turns out that my group is isomorphic to <m>\Z_8</m>, and that there is an isomorphism <m>f: G \to \Z_8</m>.
            <ol permid="DvK">
              <li permid="vRl">
                <p permid="sWF">
                  In <m>G</m>,                  <m>a \oplus b = c</m>.  Also, <m>f(a) = 3</m> and <m>f(b) = 4</m>.  What is <m>f(c)</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="bYu">
                <p permid="ZdO">
                  If <m>f(d) = 2</m>, what is <m>d\oplus d</m>?  Further, prove that <m>d\inv = a\oplus a</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="QPv">
          <p permid="Wji">
            <ol permid="XoB">
              <li permid="IfD">
                <p permid="FkX">
                  We have <m>f(a \oplus b) = f(a)+f(b)</m>.  But <m>f(a \oplus b) = f(c)</m> and <m>f(a) + f(b) = 3 + 4 = 7</m> so <m>f(c) = 7</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li permid="omM">
                <p permid="lsg">
                  We know that <m>f(d\oplus d) = f(d)+f(d) = 2+2 = 4</m>.  So <m>d \oplus d = b</m>.  As for the inverse: we need <m>f(d\inv) = 6</m>, and <m>f(a) = 3</m>, so <m>f(a \oplus a) = f(d\inv)</m>.  Since <m>f</m> is injective, we see that <m>d\inv = a\oplus a</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="qxy">
        <statement>
          <p permid="Sjj">
            Show that <m>U(5)</m> is isomorphic to <m>U(10)</m>, but <m>U(12)</m> is not.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="wWE">
          <p permid="Cqr">
            Define <m>f:U(5) \to U(10)</m> by <m>f = \begin{pmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 3 \amp 7 \amp 9\end{pmatrix}</m>.  By inspection, <m>f</m> is a bijection.  To check that it is an isomorphism, we need to check the homomorphism property <m>f(xy) = f(x)f(y)</m>.  This means checking lots of pairs.  For example, <m>ff(2\cdot 3) = f(1) = 1 = 3\cdot 7 = f(2)f(3)</m>.  You can also note that <m>U(5)</m> is cyclic with generator <m>2</m>, and <m>U(10)</m> is cyclic with generator <m>3</m>, so sending <m>2</m> to <m>3</m> will determine the isomorphism.
          </p>
          <p permid="ixA">
            As for <m>U(12)</m>, it cannot be isomorphic to <m>U(10)</m> or <m>U(5)</m>, since <m>U(12)</m> is not cyclic. Alternatively, note that every element in <m>U(12)</m> is its own inverse, but this is not true about the other groups.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="WEH">
        <statement>
          <p permid="yqs">
            Let <m>\phi:G \to H</m> be an isomorphism.  Show that <m>\phi(x) = e_H</m> if and only if <m>x = e_G</m>, where <m>e_G</m> and <m>e_H</m> are the identities of <m>G</m> and <m>H</m>, respectively.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint permid="ddN">
          <p permid="IPx">
            Since <m>\phi</m> is a bijection, it is enough to prove that <m>\phi(e_G) = e_H</m>.  Note that <m>e_G = e_G^2</m>.  Use the homomorphism property.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="CLQ">
        <statement>
          <p permid="exB">
            Let <m>G = \R \setminus \{-1\}</m> 
            with the operation <m>\ast</m> 
            defined by <me permid="MtX">
              a \ast b = a+b+ab.
            </me>
            We previously saw that <m>G</m> with this operation is a group.  Show that <m>(G, \ast)</m> is isomprhic to the multiplicative group of nonzero real numbers <m>\R^*</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint permid="JkW">
          <p permid="oWG">
            You need to define the isomorphism <m>f:G \to \R^*</m>.  A good place to start would be to decide what the identity is in each group.  Guess a reasonable function that sends the identity in <m>G</m> to the identity in <m>\R^*</m>.
          </p>
        </hint>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="iSZ">
        <statement>
          <p permid="KEK">
            True or false: if <m>\phi:G \to H</m> is an isomorphism, then <m>\phi(a^n) = (\phi(a))^n</m> for all <m>a \in G</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="psf">
          <p permid="OEJ">
            True.  <m>\phi(a^2) = \phi(a\cdot a) = \phi(a)\phi(a) = (\phi(a))^2</m>.  You can generalize this by induction: <m>\phi(a\cdot a^{n-1}) = \phi(a)(\phi(a))^{n-1}</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
