<exercises xml:id="practice-homomorph" permid="FGw">
  <title>Practice Problems</title>
  <exercise permid="boA">
    <statement>
      <p permid="Dal">
            Let <m>\DR</m> represent the group of all differentiable functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>, under addition, and <m>\FR</m> be the group of all functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>, under addition.  Let <m>\phi:\DR\to \FR</m> be given by <m>\phi(f) = f'</m> (the derivative of <m>f</m>).  Prove that <m>\phi</m> is a homomorphism and describe its kernel.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="hNG">
      <p permid="uLS">
            Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be functions in <m>\DR</m>.  Then <m>\phi(f+g) = (f+g)' = f' + g' = \phi(f) + \phi(g)</m>, using the additive property of derivatives.  Thus <m>\phi</m> is a homomorphism.
      </p>

      <p permid="aTb">
            The kernel of <m>\phi</m> is the set of all differentiable functions whose derivative is 0.  From calculus, we know that these are exactly the constant functions.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="HvJ">
    <statement>
      <p permid="jhu">
            Let <m>\phi: \Z \to \Z</m> be given by <m>\phi(n) = 5n</m>.  Prove that <m>\phi</m> is a group homomorphism.  Find the kernel and image of <m>\phi</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="NUP">
      <p permid="Hak">
            We have <m>\phi(a+b) = 5(a+b) = 5a+5b = \phi(a) + \phi(b)</m>, so <m>\phi</m> is a homomorphism.  The image of <m>\phi</m> will be <m>5\Z</m>.  The kernel is <m>\{0\}</m> (as you will show below, this is not surprising since <m>\phi</m> is injective).
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="nCS">
    <statement>
      <p permid="PoD">
            If <m>G</m> is an abelian group, show that <m>\phi: G \to G</m> defined by <m>\phi(g) = g^2</m> is a homomorphism.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="ubY">
      <p permid="nht">
            We have <m>\phi(ab) = (ab)^2 = a^2b^2</m> since <m>G</m> is abelian.  But <m>\phi(a)\phi(b) = a^2 b^2</m>, so we see that <m>\phi</m> satisfies the homomorphism property.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="TKb">
    <statement>
      <p permid="vvM">
            How many homomorphisms from <m>\Z_7</m> to <m>\Z_{10}</m> are there?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="ajh">
      <p permid="ToC">
            Only one: the trivial homomorphism.  There are only two possible kernels: <m>\{0\}</m> or <m>\Z_7</m> (since there are only two subgroups of <m>\Z_7</m>).  If <m>\{0\}</m> is the kernel, then the homomorphism will be injective.  But that would mean that the image of the homomorphism would be a 7 elements subgroup of <m>\Z_{10}</m> which is impossible.  Thus the kernel can only be <m>\Z_{7}</m> which gives the trivial homomorphism (<m>\phi(x) = 0</m> for all <m>x</m>).
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
</exercises>


