<exercises xml:id="practice-fht" permid="RUO">
  <title>Practice Problems</title>
  <exercise permid="fYt">
    <statement>
      <p permid="HKe">
            Describe all the homomorphisms from <m>\Z_{24}</m> to <m>\Z_{18}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint permid="SEI">
      <p permid="tGz">
            The kernel of a homomorphism must be a subgroup of the domain and the image must be a subgroup of the codomain.  Further, a generator must map to a generator.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution permid="mxz">
      <p permid="zvL">
            The possible kernels are the subgroups of <m>\Z_{24}</m>.  We could have <m>K = \Z_{24}</m>, and this gives the trivial homomorphism (everything goes to 0).  Our next possible kernel is <m>\langle 2 \rangle = \{0, 2, 4, \ldots, 22\}</m>.  We can then send everything else to <m>9 \in \Z_{18}</m>.
      </p>

      <p permid="fCU">
            Now take <m>K = \langle 3 \rangle = \{0, 3, 6, \ldots, 21\}</m>.  We know that <m>\Z_{24}/K \cong H</m> where <m>H</m> is the image of the homomorphism.  So we must have a 3-element subgroup of <m>\Z_{18}</m> as the image of the homomorphism.  Send <m>1</m> to <m>6</m> and <m>2</m> to 12, and so on.
      </p>

      <p permid="LKd">
            There is not a subgroup of <m>\Z_{18}</m> containing 4 elements (since <m>4</m> does not divide 18), so it is impossible for us to have a kernel <m>\langle 4 \rangle</m>.  The next possible subgroup the kernel could be is <m>\langle 6 \rangle = \{0, 6, 12, 18\}</m>, which would give us 6 cosets.  There is a subgroup of order 6 in <m>\Z_{18}</m>, namely <m>\langle 3 \rangle = \{0, 3, 6, 9, 12, 15\}</m>.  So we can define <m>\phi(n) = 3n</m> as the homomorphism.
      </p>

      <p permid="rRm">
            The kernel <m>K = \langle 8 \rangle</m> is not possible, nor is <m>K = \langle 12 \rangle</m>.  Thus we have all of the homomorphisms described.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="MfC">
    <statement>
      <p permid="nRn">
            Prove that <m>\Z/\langle 5\rangle \cong \Z_5</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="yLR">
      <p permid="XYv">
            Define <m>\psi:\Z \to \Z_5</m> by <m>\psi(x) = x \pmod{5}</m>.  That is, send every element in <m>\Z</m> to its remainder when divided by 5.  The kernel of <m>\psi</m> is <m>\langle 5\rangle</m>, so by the Fundamental Homomorphism Theorem, <m>\Z/\langle 5 \rangle \cong \Z_5</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="smL">
    <statement>
      <p permid="TYw">
            Let <m>\FR</m> be the set of all functions <m>f:\R to \R</m> under addition.  Let <m>B = \{f \in \FR \st f(0) = 0\}</m>.  Prove that <m>\FR/B \cong \R</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <hint permid="Laj">
      <p permid="ZNI">
            Define a surjective homomorphism <m>\psi:\FR \to \R</m> and use the FHT.
      </p>
    </hint>
    <solution permid="eTa">
      <p permid="EfE">
            Define a surjective homomorphism <m>\psi:\FR \to \R</m> by <m>\psi(f) = f(0)</m>.  That is, <m>\psi</m> sends a function to its <m>y</m>-intercept.  It is easy to check this is a homomorphism: <m>\psi(f+g) = (f+g)(0) = f(0) + g(0) = \psi(f)+ \psi(g)</m>.  Also, it is clearly surjective since every real number <m>c</m> is the <m>y</m>-intercept for the constant function <m>f(x) = c</m>.  Further, the kernel of <m>\psi</m> is precisely <m>B</m>.
      </p>
      <p permid="kmN">
            Thus, by the Fundamental Homomorphism Theorem, <m>\FR/B \cong \R</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise permid="YtU">
    <statement>
      <p permid="AfF">
            How many homomorphic images are there of <m>D_4</m>?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="rhs">
      <p permid="QtW">
            Suppose <m>H</m> is a homomorphic image of <m>D_4</m>.  Then <m>H \cong D_4/K</m> where <m>K</m> is the kernel of the homomorphism.  We know that <m>K</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>D_4</m>, which limits the number of possibilities for <m>K</m>.  We could have <m>K = \{r_0\}</m> or <m>k = D_4</m>, in which case we find that <m>H \cong D_4</m> or <m>H \cong \{e\}</m>, respetively.
      </p>

      <p permid="wBf">
            The other normal subgroups of <m>D_4</m> are the three 4-element subgroups, and <m>\{r_0, r_2\}</m>.  For any of the 4-element subgroups, <m>D_4/K</m> would have size <m>2</m>, so this would say that <m>H \cong \Z_2</m> (since that is the only 2-element group).
      </p>
      <p permid="cIo">
            For <m>K = \{r_0, r_2\}</m>, we will have <m>|H| = 4</m>, so there are two possibilities: <m>\Z_4</m> or <m>\Z_2 \times \Z_2</m>.  Now any element not in this kernel, if you square it, you will get something in the kernel.  That is, <m>(aK)^2 = a^2K = K</m> for all <m>a \in D_4</m>.  Thus <m>D_4/K \cong \Z_2\times \Z_2</m>.    
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>
</exercises>


